In `src/app.ts`, the `makeActionButton(label, handler)` helper attaches a click handler that may be async (the Delete/Move/Copy handlers all do `await api.X(...)`). If the API call rejects (e.g., the server returns 400 Bad Request for an invalid destination, or 500 for a server error), the rejection becomes an unhandled promise rejection — silently swallowed or surfaced only in the browser console, with no feedback to the user. Fix: in `makeActionButton`, wrap the handler invocation so that if it throws or rejects, the error is surfaced to the user. Recommended approach: the wrapper calls `Promise.resolve(handler()).catch(err => { statusEl.textContent = 'Error: ' + (err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err)); })` (or similar). The handler may now be async without leaking a rejection. Do NOT change the success-path behavior — when the handler resolves normally, no error message is shown. (Note: the status-footer error display is consistent with how `render()` already surfaces fetch errors, so this gives the user a single, consistent error surface.) Verification: `npm test` passes; the test-writing phase may add a test where a Delete/Move/Copy API call rejects and assert the error appears in `.status` (or whatever surface the implementer chose).

